-- Sample scholarship data — run after schema.sql in the Supabase SQL editor
-- Uses ON CONFLICT so re-running updates existing rows rather than failing

insert into public.scholarships (title, country, field, degree_level, deadline, link, description, eligibility) values

-- United States
('Fulbright Foreign Student Program', 'United States', 'Arts & Humanities', 'masters', '2026-10-01', 'https://foreign.fulbrightonline.org/', 'The Fulbright Foreign Student Program is the United States government''s flagship international exchange scholarship, administered by the U.S. Department of State. It enables graduate students, artists, and young professionals from abroad to study and conduct research in the United States for one to two academic years. The program covers full tuition fees, a monthly living stipend, health insurance, and round-trip airfare, allowing scholars to fully concentrate on their academic and professional development. Beyond funding, Fulbright Scholars join a global network of over 400,000 alumni across more than 160 countries, including heads of state, Nobel laureates, and leading scientists. The program places strong emphasis on mutual understanding between cultures, and scholars are expected to serve as ambassadors of their home countries while in the US.', 'Open to citizens of participating countries outside the US. Applicants must hold a bachelor''s degree or equivalent, demonstrate English proficiency, and show strong academic and leadership records. US citizenship or permanent residency is not eligible. Selected candidates must commit to returning to their home country after completion.'),

('NSF Graduate Research Fellowship', 'United States', 'Natural Sciences', 'phd', '2026-10-15', 'https://www.nsfgrfp.org/', 'The National Science Foundation Graduate Research Fellowship Program (NSF GRFP) is one of the most prestigious graduate fellowships in the United States, providing three years of financial support within a five-year fellowship period. Fellows receive an annual stipend of $37,000 and a $16,000 cost-of-education allowance paid to their institution. The fellowship supports outstanding graduate students in NSF-supported STEM disciplines who are pursuing research-based master''s and doctoral degrees. NSF Fellows are recognized by universities, industry, and government as among the most promising scientists and engineers emerging from the US. Recipients gain access to international research and professional development opportunities through supplemental funding programs and collaborations with national laboratories.', 'Open to US citizens, nationals, and permanent residents who are in the early stages of their graduate study (first or second year). Applicants must be pursuing a research-based master''s or doctoral degree in an NSF-supported STEM field. Students who have completed more than 12 months of graduate study are ineligible.'),

('Gates Millennium Scholars Program', 'United States', 'Computer Science', 'undergraduate', '2026-12-15', 'https://gmsp.org/', 'The Gates Millennium Scholars (GMS) Program, funded by the Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation, provides outstanding minority students with full scholarships to pursue undergraduate and graduate degrees in any discipline, with a particular focus on STEM fields. The scholarship covers full unmet financial need — including tuition, room, board, books, and personal expenses — for the duration of the recipient''s undergraduate studies. High-achieving scholars may also receive funding to continue into graduate programs in computer science, education, engineering, library science, mathematics, public health, or science. The program also provides a robust leadership development component, connecting scholars with mentors, internship opportunities, and a network of over 20,000 GMS alumni who span every major sector. Selection is highly competitive; the program aims to develop the next generation of diverse American leaders.', 'Applicants must be African American, American Indian/Alaska Native, Asian Pacific Islander American, or Hispanic American; be a US citizen, national, or permanent resident; maintain a cumulative GPA of 3.3 or above; and demonstrate significant financial need as defined by federal guidelines.'),

('Knight-Hennessy Scholars', 'United States', 'Public Policy', 'masters', '2026-10-01', 'https://knight-hennessy.stanford.edu/', 'Knight-Hennessy Scholars is one of the world''s largest fully endowed graduate scholarship programs, housed at Stanford University and funded by a $750 million gift from Phil Knight and his family. Up to 100 scholars are selected annually from around the world to pursue any graduate degree at Stanford, including joint and dual degrees across law, business, medicine, engineering, education, and the arts. The program provides full tuition, a living stipend, travel, and a one-time enrichment fund for each scholar throughout their Stanford studies. Beyond funding, scholars participate in a three-year leadership curriculum designed to cultivate collaborative, courageous, and innovative leaders equipped to address the world''s most complex challenges. The cohort-based model fosters lifelong connections across disciplines and nationalities.', 'Open to applicants worldwide who have received their first undergraduate degree within the past seven years. Applicants must be admitted to a Stanford graduate degree programme. There are no restrictions on nationality, field of study, age, or professional background. Selection is based on independence of thought, purposeful leadership, and civic mindset.'),

-- United Kingdom
('Chevening Scholarships', 'United Kingdom', 'Public Policy', 'masters', '2026-11-05', 'https://www.chevening.org/', 'Chevening Scholarships are the UK government''s flagship international scholarship programme, funded by the Foreign, Commonwealth & Development Office and partner organisations. The programme offers full financial support for a one-year master''s degree at any UK university to outstanding emerging leaders from around the world. Chevening covers tuition fees, a monthly living allowance, travel to and from the UK, and an arrival and departure allowance. Since its establishment in 1983, more than 50,000 Chevening Scholars have graduated from the programme and gone on to become presidents, prime ministers, Nobel Prize winners, prominent journalists, and leading academics. Scholars gain access to an exclusive global alumni network and are expected to return home after their studies to contribute to national development and maintain lasting connections with the UK.', 'Applicants must be citizens of a Chevening-eligible country, have at least two years of work experience, hold an undergraduate degree that will gain entry to a UK university, and be able to return to their home country for a minimum of two years after the scholarship ends. Previous Chevening Scholars and current UK residents are not eligible.'),

('Rhodes Scholarship', 'United Kingdom', 'Arts & Humanities', 'masters', '2026-08-01', 'https://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/', 'The Rhodes Scholarship is the oldest and arguably most prestigious international scholarship programme in the world, established in 1902 under the will of Cecil John Rhodes. It funds postgraduate study at the University of Oxford for exceptional students from more than 60 countries, covering all university and college fees, a personal stipend, and a travel allowance. Rhodes Scholars are chosen not solely for their outstanding scholarly achievements but for their character, commitment to others and to the common good, and potential for leadership in whatever domains their careers may take them. Most scholars pursue one or two years of study at Oxford; some go on to doctoral research. Among the programme''s distinguished alumni are US Presidents, Prime Ministers, Supreme Court justices, Nobel laureates, and leaders across business, science, and the arts.', 'Open to young people from eligible countries who are typically between 18–28 years of age (varies by constituency). Candidates must demonstrate intellectual distinction, character, leadership, and commitment to service. Applicants must hold or expect to hold a bachelor''s degree before taking up the scholarship. Married candidates may apply.'),

('Commonwealth Scholarship', 'United Kingdom', 'Medicine & Health', 'phd', '2026-12-01', 'https://cscuk.fcdo.gov.uk/', 'Commonwealth Scholarships are funded by the UK government and offered to citizens of Commonwealth countries to pursue postgraduate study or research in the United Kingdom. The scholarships are administered by the Commonwealth Scholarship Commission (CSC) and aim to contribute to the UK''s international development goals by building the capacity of talented individuals who will make a difference in their home countries. The award covers university tuition fees, a monthly living allowance, a travel grant, and an arrival allowance. In the field of Medicine and Health, scholars typically conduct PhD research at leading UK universities including Oxford, Cambridge, Imperial College London, and the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine. The programme prioritises candidates whose studies are aligned with development needs in their home country.', 'Open to citizens and permanent residents of Commonwealth countries who are applying to study at a UK university. Applicants must be available to take up the scholarship by the start of the UK academic year, be unable to pursue the study without the scholarship, and hold a first degree of at least upper second class (2:1) standard.'),

-- Germany
('DAAD Scholarship', 'Germany', 'Engineering', 'masters', '2026-11-15', 'https://www.daad.de/en/', 'The German Academic Exchange Service (DAAD) is the world''s largest funding organisation for the international exchange of students and researchers. DAAD scholarships enable international graduates and postgraduates to pursue master''s degrees or conduct research at German universities and research institutions for periods ranging from one month to two years. The scholarship covers a monthly stipend to cover living expenses, health insurance, and in some programmes, travel costs and a study and research allowance. Germany is home to some of the world''s top-ranked engineering institutions, including TU Munich, RWTH Aachen, and KIT, making DAAD an exceptional gateway to world-class technical education. The scholarship is available in both English-taught and German-taught programmes, and DAAD offers intensive German language courses to prepare recipients before their studies begin.', 'Open to international students who hold an above-average bachelor''s degree. Applicants typically need at least two years of professional experience after completing their first academic degree. German language skills may be required depending on the programme. Applications must be submitted through the applicant''s home country DAAD office.'),

('Konrad-Adenauer-Stiftung Scholarship', 'Germany', 'Social Sciences', 'phd', '2026-07-15', 'https://www.kas.de/en/', 'The Konrad-Adenauer-Stiftung (KAS) Scholarship Programme supports academically gifted doctoral students at German universities who demonstrate a strong commitment to the social and political principles of Christian democracy. Funded by the German government, KAS scholarships are awarded to both German and international students whose research focuses on political science, sociology, law, economics, or related social sciences. Recipients receive a monthly stipend, additional family allowances where applicable, and a book and material allowance. Beyond financial support, KAS organises an extensive programme of seminars, conferences, workshops, and international study trips that connect scholars with leading thinkers, politicians, and practitioners. Scholars become part of a global network of alumni who share a commitment to democracy, the rule of law, and a united Europe.', 'Open to German and foreign students enrolled in or applying for a doctoral programme at a German university. Applicants must demonstrate above-average academic performance, social commitment, and alignment with democratic and Christian-democratic values. Foreign applicants must have a strong command of German.'),

-- Australia
('Australia Awards Scholarships', 'Australia', 'Agriculture', 'masters', '2026-04-30', 'https://www.australiaawards.gov.au/', 'Australia Awards Scholarships are long-term awards funded by the Australian Government and administered by the Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade (DFAT). They provide citizens from eligible developing countries in the Indo-Pacific, Africa, and the Middle East with the opportunity to undertake full-time undergraduate or postgraduate study at participating Australian universities. The scholarship covers full tuition fees, return airfare, an establishment allowance, a monthly living stipend, health cover through Overseas Student Health Cover (OSHC), and academic support. In the field of agriculture, Australia Awards scholars gain access to world-leading research institutions and practical training opportunities that address food security, sustainable farming, and rural development challenges directly relevant to their home countries. Scholars are expected to return home after completing their studies and use their skills to contribute to development.', 'Open to citizens of eligible countries in the Indo-Pacific region, Africa, and the Middle East. Applicants must not hold Australian or New Zealand citizenship or permanent residency, must be outside Australia at the time of application, and must commit to returning to their home country for at least two years after completing their studies.'),

('Endeavour Leadership Program', 'Australia', 'Environmental Science', 'phd', '2026-06-30', 'https://internationaleducation.gov.au/', 'The Endeavour Leadership Program is the Australian Government''s internationally competitive, merit-based scholarship programme providing opportunities for Australians to undertake study, research, or professional development abroad, and for overseas citizens to do the same in Australia. For international applicants, the Endeavour Research Fellowship and Postgraduate Scholarship streams support high-achieving individuals to conduct PhD or postdoctoral research at Australian institutions for up to four years. Scholars in environmental science gain access to Australia''s world-class research infrastructure in marine ecology, climate science, biodiversity, and sustainability. Benefits include a monthly stipend, establishment allowance, travel allowance, tuition fees, and health and travel insurance. Recipients are selected on the basis of academic excellence, research quality, and demonstrated commitment to their field.', 'Open to citizens of eligible countries in the Asia-Pacific, Middle East, Europe, and Americas regions. Applicants must not be Australian citizens or permanent residents. Candidates must demonstrate high academic achievement and the capacity to contribute to their community. The scholarship requires full-time enrolment at an Australian institution.'),

-- Canada
('Vanier Canada Graduate Scholarships', 'Canada', 'Medicine & Health', 'phd', '2026-11-01', 'https://vanier.gc.ca/', 'The Vanier Canada Graduate Scholarships (Vanier CGS) programme was created to attract and retain world-class doctoral students and to establish Canada as a global centre of excellence in research and higher education. Valued at $50,000 per year for three years, Vanier CGS is awarded to doctoral students who demonstrate strong academic achievement, research potential, and leadership ability. The programme is administered by Canada''s three federal research agencies — CIHR, NSERC, and SSHRC — and is available to both Canadian and international students at eligible Canadian universities. In Medicine and Health, Vanier scholars pursue cutting-edge doctoral research in areas including clinical trials, health systems, epidemiology, biomedical science, and global health. Recipients benefit from institutional support, networking events, and recognition as part of Canada''s most elite community of graduate researchers.', 'Open to both Canadian and international students who are nominated by a Canadian university. Candidates must be pursuing their first doctoral degree, have an overall average of at least A- in the last two completed years of study, and demonstrate leadership ability and a high standard of scholarly achievement in graduate and undergraduate studies.'),

('Trudeau Foundation Scholarship', 'Canada', 'Social Sciences', 'phd', '2026-12-01', 'https://www.trudeaufoundation.ca/', 'The Pierre Elliott Trudeau Foundation Scholarship is one of Canada''s most distinguished doctoral awards, recognising scholars whose research engages directly with pressing public policy questions and whose work holds the potential to positively impact Canadian and global society. Up to 15 scholars are selected annually from a highly competitive pool of applicants from across Canada. The scholarship provides a $60,000 annual award for up to four years, supplemented by a $20,000 travel and professional development allowance per year. Scholars work within the Foundation''s four thematic areas: engaged citizenship, human rights and dignity, responsible citizenship, and people and their natural environment. Beyond funding, scholars participate in intensive annual retreats, mentorship from Foundation Fellows, and a vibrant intellectual community of past and present scholars who shape the national conversation.', 'Open to Canadian citizens, permanent residents, and protected persons enrolled in or applying to a doctoral programme at a Canadian university. Research must engage with at least one of the Foundation''s four thematic areas. Applicants must demonstrate academic excellence, social commitment, and a vision for Canada''s role in the world.'),

-- Netherlands
('Holland Scholarship', 'Netherlands', 'Business', 'masters', '2027-01-31', 'https://www.studyinholland.nl/scholarships/', 'The Holland Scholarship is funded by the Dutch Ministry of Education, Culture and Science and offered by Dutch research universities and universities of applied sciences to attract talented students from outside the European Economic Area. The scholarship provides a one-time grant of EUR 5,000 to help cover the costs of the first year of a bachelor''s or master''s programme in the Netherlands. The Netherlands is consistently ranked among the world''s top education destinations, and its universities offer a wide range of English-taught business and management programmes at institutions such as the University of Amsterdam, Erasmus University Rotterdam, and Maastricht University. Studying in the Netherlands provides access to one of Europe''s strongest economies, a diverse international student community, and excellent professional networks in trade, logistics, finance, and technology.', 'Open to non-EEA international students who are applying to a full-time bachelor''s or master''s programme at a participating Dutch research university or university of applied sciences. Applicants must be applying for the first time to a Dutch higher education institution. Previous degree holders from the Netherlands are not eligible.'),

('Leiden Excellence Scholarship', 'Netherlands', 'Law', 'masters', '2026-09-01', 'https://www.universiteitleiden.nl/scholarships/', 'The Leiden Excellence Scholarship (LExS) is a merit-based award offered by Leiden University — one of Europe''s oldest and most prestigious universities, founded in 1575 — to outstanding international students from outside the European Economic Area. The scholarship supports students pursuing an English-taught master''s programme at Leiden University and is available in three tiers: a 50% tuition waiver, a 75% tuition waiver, or a 100% tuition waiver covering the full statutory tuition fee. Leiden University''s Law Faculty is internationally renowned, ranked among the top law schools globally, and offers specialisms in public international law, European law, criminal law, and legal theory. LExS recipients benefit from Leiden''s rich intellectual tradition, small class sizes, and a global alumni network that spans government, international organisations, and leading law firms.', 'Open to non-EEA students who have been admitted to a Leiden University English-taught master''s programme. Applicants must have completed a bachelor''s degree with outstanding academic results (typically a GPA in the top 10% of their class). The scholarship cannot be combined with other Leiden University scholarships.'),

-- Japan
('MEXT Scholarship', 'Japan', 'Engineering', 'masters', '2026-05-31', 'https://www.studyinjapan.go.jp/en/stype/mext/', 'The Japanese Government (MEXT) Scholarship is offered by Japan''s Ministry of Education, Culture, Sports, Science and Technology to international students who wish to study at Japanese universities as research students, undergraduate students, or students in specialised training colleges. For graduate-level engineering research, the scholarship typically covers full tuition fees, a monthly stipend of approximately ¥143,000 (research students) to ¥145,000 (master''s students), and return airfare. Recipients also complete a Japanese language preparation course before beginning their studies. Japan is a global leader in robotics, civil engineering, electrical engineering, and materials science, and MEXT scholars gain access to world-class laboratories and industry partnerships at universities such as Tokyo Institute of Technology, Osaka University, and Tohoku University. The scholarship period is typically two years for a master''s degree, with the possibility of extension.', 'Open to nationals of countries with diplomatic relations with Japan. Applicants must be under 35 years of age (for research students), have completed or be completing undergraduate education, and demonstrate Japanese language ability or willingness to learn. Applications are submitted via the Japanese Embassy in the applicant''s home country.'),

('JASSO Honors Scholarship', 'Japan', 'Natural Sciences', 'phd', '2026-08-31', 'https://www.jasso.or.jp/en/', 'The Japan Student Services Organization (JASSO) Honors Scholarship for Privately-Financed International Students provides monthly financial support to international students enrolled as regular students at Japanese universities, graduate schools, junior colleges, or colleges of technology. The scholarship is intended to assist outstanding international students who are self-financing their education in Japan and face financial difficulty. Monthly awards range from ¥48,000 for undergraduate students to ¥65,000 for graduate students. In the natural sciences, JASSO scholars are embedded in Japan''s leading research ecosystem, which ranks among the world''s top five in scientific output and is home to Nobel Prize-winning research in physics, chemistry, and medicine. Scholars benefit from structured mentorship, access to university research facilities, and a network connecting them with Japan''s vibrant scientific and academic community.', 'Open to international students currently enrolled at a Japanese university as regular students. Candidates must demonstrate excellent academic performance, strong conduct, and financial need. Recipients must maintain satisfactory academic progress throughout the scholarship period and must not be receiving other Japanese government scholarships simultaneously.'),

-- Switzerland
('Swiss Government Excellence Scholarships', 'Switzerland', 'Natural Sciences', 'phd', '2026-12-15', 'https://www.sbfi.admin.ch/scholarships/', 'The Swiss Government Excellence Scholarships are awarded by the Swiss Confederation to promote international exchange and research cooperation between Switzerland and over 180 countries. The scholarships are offered to postgraduate researchers, PhD candidates, and artists for study and research at Swiss public universities or recognised institutions. Recipients benefit from full coverage of living expenses via a monthly stipend of CHF 1,920, exemption from cantonal tuition fees at Swiss universities, a health insurance contribution, and accommodation support. Switzerland hosts four of the world''s top 15 universities — ETH Zurich, EPFL, University of Zurich, and the University of Basel — making it one of the most sought-after destinations for natural sciences research globally. Scholars are selected on scientific merit and the quality of their research proposal, with admission subject to acceptance by a Swiss academic host.', 'Open to citizens of eligible countries who hold a master''s degree (for PhD applicants) or a PhD (for postdoctoral applicants). Candidates must be no older than 35 years for PhD scholarships and 45 years for postdoctoral fellowships. Swiss citizens and current residents of Switzerland are not eligible. Applications are submitted through the Swiss Embassy.'),

-- Sweden
('Swedish Institute Scholarships', 'Sweden', 'Environmental Science', 'masters', '2027-02-10', 'https://si.se/en/apply/scholarships/', 'The Swedish Institute Scholarships for Global Professionals (SISGP) is a highly competitive scholarship programme that funds international professionals to pursue a one- or two-year master''s degree at a Swedish university. The scholarship covers full tuition fees, a monthly living allowance of SEK 11,000, travel grants, and insurance. Sweden is a world leader in sustainable development, clean technology, and environmental policy, and Swedish universities consistently rank among the best globally for environmental science, urban planning, and climate research. Beyond academic study, SI scholars participate in the Sweden-based SI Network for Future Global Leaders — a curated leadership programme offering workshops, study visits, meetings with Swedish industry leaders, and a mentorship scheme. The programme has a clear vision of developing a global network of leaders committed to sustainability and positive change.', 'Open to citizens of eligible countries in Asia, Africa, the Middle East, Eastern Europe, and Latin America. Applicants must have a bachelor''s degree, at least 3,000 hours of work experience, and demonstrate leadership potential and a commitment to contributing to sustainable development in their home country after completing the degree.'),

-- Singapore
('NUS Research Scholarship', 'Singapore', 'Computer Science', 'phd', '2027-03-01', 'https://nusgs.nus.edu.sg/scholarships/', 'The NUS Research Scholarship (NRS) is offered by the National University of Singapore — consistently ranked Asia''s top university and among the world''s top 15 globally — to attract outstanding students to pursue doctoral research across all disciplines. The scholarship provides full tuition fee subsidy, a monthly stipend of SGD 2,000 (enhanced to SGD 2,500 for students who have passed their qualifying examination), and a generous housing allowance. NUS''s School of Computing is one of the top-ranked computer science faculties in the world, with research strengths spanning artificial intelligence, cybersecurity, data science, human-computer interaction, and distributed systems. PhD students work closely with internationally recognised faculty, have access to state-of-the-art research labs, and benefit from NUS''s deep industry partnerships with global technology companies including Google, Microsoft, Alibaba, and Sea Group.', 'Open to both Singapore citizens and international applicants who have been admitted to an NUS PhD programme. Applicants must hold a good bachelor''s degree with honours (upper second class or equivalent) or a master''s degree in a relevant field. Proficiency in English is required. The scholarship is tenable for up to four years subject to satisfactory academic progress.'),

-- France
('Eiffel Excellence Scholarship', 'France', 'Engineering', 'masters', '2027-01-10', 'https://www.campusfrance.org/en/eiffel-scholarship-program-of-excellence', 'The Eiffel Excellence Scholarship Programme was established by the French Ministry for Europe and Foreign Affairs to enable French higher education institutions to attract top foreign students to enrol in their master''s and PhD programmes. The scholarship is aimed at training future foreign decision-makers in the private and public sectors. It covers a monthly stipend of EUR 1,181 for master''s students, international travel costs, health insurance, and cultural activities. France is home to prestigious engineering grandes écoles such as École Polytechnique, CentraleSupélec, and Arts et Métiers, which rank consistently among Europe''s finest technical institutions. The Eiffel Programme particularly targets candidates from emerging economies in Asia, the Americas, the Middle East, and sub-Saharan Africa, with priority given to students under 30 applying to master''s programmes and under 35 for PhD programmes.', 'Open to international students who are not French nationals and who do not reside in France at the time of application. Candidates must be nominated by the head of a French higher education institution — individual applications are not accepted. Priority is given to citizens of target countries in Asia, the Americas, Africa, and the Middle East. Applicants must demonstrate outstanding academic achievement.'),

('French Government BGF Scholarship', 'France', 'Arts & Humanities', 'phd', '2026-03-31', 'https://www.campusfrance.org/en/bgf', 'The French Government Scholarship (Bourse du Gouvernement Français, BGF) is awarded by the French Ministry for Europe and Foreign Affairs through its network of Embassies and Institutes Français worldwide. It supports international students at all levels — from undergraduate to doctoral — wishing to pursue studies in France. For doctoral candidates in the humanities, the scholarship typically covers tuition fees, a monthly living allowance, and complementary benefits such as social security registration assistance and cultural access. France''s universities and grandes écoles host some of the world''s leading humanities research centres, particularly in philosophy, history, linguistics, literary studies, and the visual arts. The BGF is especially valued for the cultural immersion it provides — scholars gain direct access to France''s extraordinary heritage, museum collections, archives, and intellectual life, with Paris ranking among the world''s top three university cities.', 'Open to foreign nationals applying to study in France. Eligibility criteria vary by country, as scholarships are administered through French Embassies and Instituts Français abroad. Applicants must demonstrate academic excellence, a clear research or study project aligned with French institutional strengths, and in many cases a working knowledge of French.'),

-- South Korea
('Korean Government Scholarship (KGSP)', 'South Korea', 'Natural Sciences', 'undergraduate', '2026-09-15', 'https://www.niied.go.kr/eng/page.do?menuIdx=351', 'The Korean Government Scholarship Program (KGSP), officially known as the Global Korea Scholarship (GKS), is a prestigious fully-funded scholarship offered by the National Institute for International Education (NIIED) under the Ministry of Education of South Korea. The programme invites outstanding international students to study at Korean universities at the undergraduate level, covering full tuition fees, a monthly living allowance of KRW 900,000, a settlement allowance, round-trip airfare, language training costs, and medical insurance. Recipients begin with a one-year Korean language training programme before commencing their undergraduate degree, enabling full academic and cultural immersion. South Korea is one of Asia''s leading knowledge economies, home to world-class universities such as Seoul National University, KAIST, POSTECH, and Yonsei University. The scholarship aims to develop lasting bonds between Korea and the international community through academic exchange.', 'Open to citizens of KGSP-eligible countries who are under 25 years of age at the time of application. Applicants must have completed secondary school (high school) with a cumulative GPA of at least 80% or equivalent. Neither the applicant nor either parent may be a Korean national. Applications are submitted through Korean Embassies in the applicant''s home country.'),

('POSTECH International Scholarship', 'South Korea', 'Engineering', 'phd', '2026-12-01', 'https://admission.postech.ac.kr/web/page.do?key=1318', 'The Pohang University of Science and Technology (POSTECH) International Scholarship is awarded to exceptional international PhD students who wish to conduct cutting-edge research at one of Asia''s premier science and technology institutions. Ranked among the world''s top 100 universities, POSTECH offers unparalleled research infrastructure across engineering disciplines including materials science, chemical engineering, mechanical engineering, electrical engineering, and industrial engineering. The scholarship provides full tuition exemption, a monthly stipend of KRW 700,000–900,000, accommodation support, and research activity funding. POSTECH''s small student-to-faculty ratio ensures that doctoral students receive intensive mentorship from leading researchers with strong industry ties to companies such as POSCO, Samsung, LG, and Hyundai. Graduates from POSTECH''s PhD programmes consistently secure positions at top global research institutions and Fortune 500 technology companies.', 'Open to international students who are not Korean nationals and who hold a bachelor''s or master''s degree in a relevant STEM field. Candidates must be admitted to a POSTECH PhD programme and demonstrate outstanding academic records and strong research potential. Proficiency in English is required; knowledge of Korean is an advantage.'),

-- China
('Chinese Government Scholarship (CSC)', 'China', 'Medicine & Health', 'masters', '2026-03-15', 'https://www.campuschina.org/scholarships/', 'The Chinese Government Scholarship (CSC) is a fully-funded scholarship programme established by the Ministry of Education of China to promote the internationalisation of Chinese higher education and strengthen cultural exchange between China and other nations. Administered by the China Scholarship Council (CSC), it supports international students at all levels — undergraduate, master''s, doctoral — at designated Chinese universities. For master''s students in medicine and health, the scholarship covers full tuition fees, on-campus accommodation, a monthly living stipend of CNY 3,000, and comprehensive medical insurance. China''s medical universities, including Peking Union Medical College, Tongji University, and Fudan University, are internationally recognised for research in traditional Chinese medicine, oncology, infectious diseases, and public health. The programme is available via two application channels: through Chinese Embassies abroad or directly through designated Chinese universities.', 'Open to non-Chinese nationals who are in good health and under 35 years of age for master''s applicants. Candidates must hold a bachelor''s degree with a strong academic record. Applicants must not currently be studying in China or receiving other Chinese government scholarships. Applications can be submitted via Chinese Embassies or the CSC online portal.'),

('Tsinghua University Scholarship for International Students', 'China', 'Computer Science', 'phd', '2026-12-31', 'https://www.tsinghua.edu.cn/en/Admissions/Graduate_Admissions.htm', 'Tsinghua University — ranked among the top 20 universities in the world and widely regarded as China''s MIT — offers a range of scholarships for outstanding international doctoral students across its academic departments. The Tsinghua University Scholarship for International Students provides full tuition waiver, a monthly living stipend, and on-campus accommodation for doctoral candidates who demonstrate exceptional research potential. Tsinghua''s Department of Computer Science and Technology is consistently ranked in the global top ten and is at the forefront of research in artificial intelligence, computer vision, natural language processing, quantum computing, and systems architecture. Doctoral candidates collaborate directly with internationally renowned faculty members and have access to major research laboratories and industry partnerships with leading Chinese and global technology firms including Huawei, Baidu, Tencent, and Alibaba.', 'Open to non-Chinese nationals who hold a master''s degree (or in exceptional cases a bachelor''s degree with outstanding achievements) from a recognised university. Applicants must demonstrate strong research capability and academic excellence. Candidates must be under 45 years of age. An application to a specific research supervisor at Tsinghua is strongly recommended before formal application.'),

-- India
('ICCR Scholarship', 'India', 'Arts & Humanities', 'masters', '2026-12-31', 'https://a2ascholarships.iccr.gov.in/', 'The Indian Council for Cultural Relations (ICCR) Scholarship Scheme is one of India''s most prominent international scholarship initiatives, offering fully-funded educational opportunities to citizens of developing and friendly countries to study at Indian universities. The programme aims to promote cultural understanding, academic exchange, and people-to-people ties between India and partner nations. Scholarships are available for undergraduate, master''s, and doctoral programmes across a wide range of disciplines, including arts, humanities, culture, social sciences, and fine arts. Recipients receive full tuition fees, a monthly stipend, accommodation in university hostels, and a book allowance. Indian universities such as Jawaharlal Nehru University (JNU), Delhi University, and Banaras Hindu University (BHU) are internationally respected for their programmes in history, literature, philosophy, linguistics, and the performing arts.', 'Open to citizens of ICCR-partner countries who apply through the Indian Embassy or High Commission in their home country. Age limits vary by programme level. Applicants must meet the academic eligibility requirements of the Indian universities they wish to attend. Knowledge of Hindi or English is generally required depending on the programme.'),

('Prime Minister''s Fellowship for Doctoral Research', 'India', 'Natural Sciences', 'phd', '2026-09-30', 'https://www.scienceandsociety-dst.org/pmfellow.html', 'The Prime Minister''s Fellowship Scheme for Doctoral Research is a joint initiative of the Confederation of Indian Industry (CII), the Science and Engineering Research Board (SERB), and industry partners aimed at fostering industry-relevant PhD research in India. It provides selected doctoral scholars with a fellowship of up to INR 70,000 per month — significantly higher than standard government fellowships — along with a research contingency grant and industry mentorship. Scholars are co-supervised by an academic institution and an industry partner, bridging the gap between foundational research and real-world application. In natural sciences, this programme funds work in biotechnology, materials, chemistry, physics, and environmental science, with research outcomes that are expected to have direct commercial and societal impact. The programme explicitly targets innovations that will strengthen India''s global scientific standing and industrial competitiveness.', 'Open to Indian nationals who have enrolled in or been admitted to a PhD programme at a recognised Indian academic institution. Candidates must have a strong academic record and must secure co-supervision from both an academic institution and a participating industry partner. Age limit is 32 years at the time of application.'),

-- Norway
('Norwegian Government Quota Scheme', 'Norway', 'Social Sciences', 'masters', '2026-12-01', 'https://hkdir.no/en/scholarships-and-loans/quota-scheme', 'The Norwegian Government Quota Scheme (now succeeded by partnership programmes) historically provided fully-funded scholarships to students from developing countries and countries in Central and Eastern Europe to pursue master''s or doctoral degrees at Norwegian universities. Under current successor frameworks, Norway continues to fund international academic exchange through NORPART and bilateral programmes, supporting students particularly from Asia, Africa, Latin America, and Eastern Europe. Norwegian universities — including the University of Oslo, NTNU, and the University of Bergen — are internationally recognised in the social sciences, particularly in development studies, peace and conflict research, human rights, and welfare state research. Norway''s generous academic culture and emphasis on equality, democracy, and sustainable development make it an outstanding destination for graduate study in the social sciences.', 'Eligibility varies by the specific partnership programme. Generally, applicants must be citizens of a partner country, hold a bachelor''s degree with strong academic results, and be applying to a master''s programme at a Norwegian university with an active partnership agreement. Norwegian language skills are an advantage but not always required for English-taught programmes.'),

('Research Council of Norway International Postdoctoral Fellowship', 'Norway', 'Environmental Science', 'phd', '2026-10-01', 'https://www.forskningsradet.no/en/', 'The Research Council of Norway (RCN) funds a range of competitive fellowship programmes supporting doctoral and postdoctoral researchers at Norwegian universities and research institutes. The International Postdoctoral Fellowship and associated PhD funding mechanisms provide salary-level stipends (typically NOK 500,000–600,000 per year), research costs, and institutional overhead. Norway is a world leader in environmental research, particularly in Arctic science, oceanography, fisheries management, carbon capture, and renewable energy. Researchers at institutions such as CICERO, NILU, the Norwegian Institute for Nature Research (NINA), and NTNU''s Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering work at the frontier of climate science and sustainability. Fellows benefit from Norway''s exceptional natural research environment and strong international collaborative networks within the EU research ecosystem.', 'Applications are typically submitted through Norwegian host institutions rather than individually. PhD funding is available to researchers enrolled at or hosted by Norwegian universities. International candidates must be associated with a Norwegian research project. Proficiency in English is required; Norwegian skills are valued for fieldwork-based research.'),

-- Ireland
('Government of Ireland International Education Scholarship', 'Ireland', 'Arts & Humanities', 'undergraduate', '2026-12-05', 'https://hea.ie/funding-governance-performance/funding/student-finance/gov-of-ireland-international-education-scholarship/', 'The Government of Ireland International Education Scholarship (GOI-IES) is a prestigious programme funded by the Irish Government and administered by the Higher Education Authority (HEA). It awards up to 60 scholarships annually to high-achieving students from non-EEA countries, covering full tuition fees and a €10,000 stipend per year for undergraduate or postgraduate study at an Irish higher education institution. Ireland''s universities — Trinity College Dublin, University College Dublin, and University College Cork among them — are world-ranked institutions with strong faculties in English literature, history, philosophy, Irish studies, and the creative arts. The scholarship is valued not only for its financial support but for placing recipients within one of Europe''s most vibrant academic communities, in a country with a rich literary and cultural heritage and a dynamic, globally connected economy.', 'Open to non-EEA nationals applying to a full-time undergraduate or postgraduate programme at a participating Irish higher education institution. Candidates must demonstrate outstanding academic achievement. Applicants must not previously have studied in Ireland. Applications are submitted through the HEA online portal.'),

('Irish Research Council Government of Ireland Postgraduate Scholarship', 'Ireland', 'Social Sciences', 'phd', '2026-11-15', 'https://research.ie/funding/goipg/', 'The Irish Research Council''s Government of Ireland Postgraduate Scholarship Programme (GOIPG) is Ireland''s premier competitive postgraduate scholarship, providing funding for doctoral researchers at Irish higher education institutions across all disciplines. The award provides a stipend of €19,000 per year for up to four years, full tuition fee payment, and an annual research expenses contribution of €2,500. The programme is open to both Irish and international students and spans the full range of arts, humanities, social sciences, STEM, and professional disciplines. Ireland''s research universities punch well above their weight in social science output, with particular strength in economics, political science, sociology, law, and education research. GOIPG scholars are integrated into a vibrant national research community, with access to the Irish Research Council''s networking events, professional development workshops, and public engagement programmes.', 'Open to applicants who are enrolled in, or about to enrol in, a PhD programme at an eligible Irish higher education institution. International applicants are eligible on equal terms with Irish nationals. Candidates must have completed a primary degree (typically a first-class or upper second-class honours bachelor''s degree) and must not have commenced their PhD studies before a specified date.'),

-- New Zealand
('New Zealand Excellence Awards', 'New Zealand', 'Agriculture', 'masters', '2026-10-31', 'https://www.education.govt.nz/our-work/international-education/new-zealand-scholarships/', 'The New Zealand Excellence Awards (NZEA) are fully-funded scholarships offered by the New Zealand government to high-achieving international students from selected countries in Asia, Latin America, and the Middle East to pursue postgraduate study in New Zealand. The scholarship covers full tuition fees, a living allowance of NZD 15,000 per year, establishment costs, and health insurance. New Zealand is a world leader in agricultural science, sustainable farming, precision agriculture, and agri-technology, with Lincoln University and Massey University consistently ranked among the world''s top agricultural research institutions. Scholars gain access to New Zealand''s unique research environment, where agriculture meets innovation — studying soil science, food systems, viticulture, animal science, and horticulture in one of the world''s most productive and diverse farming landscapes.', 'Open to citizens of NZEA-eligible countries who are applying to a full-time postgraduate degree (master''s or PhD) at a New Zealand university. Applicants must not hold New Zealand or Australian citizenship or permanent residency. Candidates are required to demonstrate academic excellence, leadership potential, and a commitment to applying their skills to benefit their home country after completing their studies.'),

('University of Auckland Doctoral Scholarship', 'New Zealand', 'Engineering', 'phd', '2026-08-15', 'https://www.auckland.ac.nz/en/study/scholarships-and-awards/find-a-scholarship/university-of-auckland-doctoral-scholarship.html', 'The University of Auckland Doctoral Scholarship is offered to high-achieving students wishing to pursue doctoral research at the University of Auckland — New Zealand''s largest and highest-ranked university, consistently placed in the global top 100. The scholarship provides a stipend of NZD 27,000 per year for up to three years, plus full tuition fees for the standard PhD duration. The University of Auckland''s Faculty of Engineering is particularly strong in civil and environmental engineering, electrical and computer engineering, chemical and materials engineering, and biomedical engineering. Doctoral students have access to Auckland''s major research centres and benefit from close proximity to New Zealand''s technology and infrastructure sector. The city of Auckland itself offers an excellent quality of life, diverse multicultural environment, and strong connections to the Asia-Pacific region.', 'Open to domestic and international students who have been accepted to enrol in a doctoral programme at the University of Auckland. Applicants must hold a master''s degree with first-class honours or equivalent. Candidates who hold an honours degree of exceptionally high standard may also be considered. International applicants must meet English language requirements.'),

-- Denmark
('Danish Government Scholarship', 'Denmark', 'Natural Sciences', 'masters', '2027-03-01', 'https://www.ufm.dk/en/education/recognition-and-transparency/transparency-tools/danish-scholarships', 'The Danish Government Scholarship is available to students from outside the EU/EEA and Switzerland who apply to study a full-degree programme at a Danish university. The scholarship is awarded on merit and covers full tuition fees and a monthly stipend of approximately DKK 6,000–6,900. Denmark consistently ranks among the world''s top countries for research quality, particularly in the natural sciences. The University of Copenhagen, Technical University of Denmark (DTU), and Aarhus University are internationally acclaimed for research in biochemistry, molecular biology, physics, and pharmaceutical sciences. Danish universities are known for their innovative, student-centred pedagogical approach, strong emphasis on independent research, and close ties with Denmark''s thriving life science and pharmaceutical industries, including major players such as Novo Nordisk and Leo Pharma.', 'Open to non-EU/EEA citizens applying to a full-degree programme at a Danish university offering the scholarship. Applications are made directly to the university, not to the government. Scholarship availability and criteria differ by institution and programme. Candidates must demonstrate outstanding academic merit and meet the admission requirements of the target programme.'),

-- Belgium
('VLIR-UOS Scholarship', 'Belgium', 'Agriculture', 'phd', '2026-02-01', 'https://www.vliruos.be/en/scholarships/', 'The VLIR-UOS Scholarships are funded by the Belgian Development Cooperation and managed by the Flemish Interuniversity Council (VLIR-UOS). They enable students from 31 countries in Africa, Asia, and Latin America to pursue English-taught master''s programmes or PhD research at Belgian universities (Flemish). The doctoral programmes focus on research that has direct relevance to sustainable development in the student''s home country. In agriculture, VLIR-UOS supports research in food security, agroecology, crop science, soil management, and rural development. Belgian universities such as KU Leuven, Ghent University, and the University of Antwerp are world-class research institutions with strong development-oriented faculties. The scholarship covers tuition, a monthly allowance, insurance, travel costs, and a research budget, making it one of the most comprehensive scholarships available for development-focused doctoral research.', 'Open to citizens of 31 eligible countries in Africa, Asia, and Latin America who are under 40 years of age at the time of application. Applicants must hold a master''s degree (for PhD) with a minimum grade equivalent to 70%. Candidates must not currently reside in a developed country and must commit to returning to their home country after completing the scholarship.'),

-- Finland
('Finland Scholarship', 'Finland', 'Engineering', 'masters', '2027-01-31', 'https://www.finnisheducation.fi/scholarships/', 'The Finland Scholarship is offered by Finnish higher education institutions to outstanding non-EU/EEA students who are required to pay tuition fees, as part of Finland''s commitment to attracting global talent to its universities. The scholarship typically covers a waiver of the full tuition fee and in some cases includes a living allowance component. Finnish universities — particularly Aalto University, Tampere University, and the University of Oulu — are globally recognised for excellence in engineering, particularly in ICT, sustainable engineering, energy technology, and forest and paper technology. Finland is consistently rated one of the world''s happiest and most innovative countries, and its universities emphasise practical problem-solving, interdisciplinary collaboration, and close industry engagement. International master''s graduates in engineering benefit from Finland''s growing tech sector and access to the broader Nordic innovation ecosystem.', 'Open to non-EU/EEA students who are subject to tuition fees and who apply to an English-taught master''s programme at a participating Finnish university. Selection is based on academic merit, with some institutions also considering motivation and future career plans. Applicants must meet the admission requirements of the target programme.'),

-- Austria
('OeAD Government Scholarship', 'Austria', 'Arts & Humanities', 'phd', '2026-03-01', 'https://oead.at/en/to-austria/grants-scholarships/', 'The OeAD (Austrian Agency for Education and Internationalisation) administers a wide range of scholarship programmes on behalf of the Austrian Federal Ministry of Education, Science and Research. These include grants for postgraduate research stays, doctoral studies, and artistic residencies in Austria. For doctoral candidates in the humanities, the scholarships typically provide a monthly grant of EUR 1,350 for up to ten months (research stays) or longer for full doctoral enrolments, plus travel contributions. Austria''s universities — the University of Vienna, Vienna University of Technology, and the University of Salzburg — have centuries-old traditions of scholarship in philosophy, music, art history, medieval history, and comparative literature. Vienna itself is one of the world''s great cultural capitals, offering unparalleled access to archives, libraries, concert halls, and museums that make it an exceptional base for humanities research.', 'Open to citizens of eligible partner countries who hold a master''s degree or equivalent and have been admitted to or are enrolled in a doctoral programme at an Austrian university. Applicants must demonstrate a specific, well-developed research project. German language proficiency is generally required for programmes at Austrian institutions, with some exceptions for English-taught doctoral programmes.'),

-- Czech Republic
('Czech Government Scholarship', 'Czech Republic', 'Social Sciences', 'undergraduate', '2026-09-01', 'https://www.dzs.cz/en/scholarships/', 'The Czech Government Scholarship Programme, administered by the Czech National Agency for International Education and Research (DZS), offers fully-funded study opportunities to international students from developing countries, as well as citizens of countries with bilateral cultural agreements with the Czech Republic, to pursue undergraduate, master''s, or doctoral degrees at Czech public universities. The scholarship covers full tuition fees at Czech public universities, a monthly allowance, accommodation, and health insurance. Czech universities — Charles University in Prague, Masaryk University in Brno, and Palacký University — are highly respected in Central Europe and have strong programmes in social sciences, political science, law, and European studies. The Czech Republic''s location at the heart of Europe provides students with direct exposure to EU policy-making and the fascinating social, political, and economic dynamics of post-communist European societies.', 'Open to citizens of developing countries and countries with bilateral cultural agreements with the Czech Republic. Applicants must not be Czech citizens or long-term residents. For undergraduate programmes, candidates must have completed secondary school. All applicants must demonstrate academic merit and commit to returning to their home country after completing their studies. Czech language courses are provided for programmes taught in Czech.'),

-- Brazil
('CAPES PrInt Scholarship', 'Brazil', 'Natural Sciences', 'phd', '2026-06-30', 'https://www.gov.br/capes/en/', 'CAPES (Coordenação de Aperfeiçoamento de Pessoal de Nível Superior) is Brazil''s federal agency for the improvement of higher education personnel and manages several international scholarship programmes. The PrInt (Programa Institucional de Internacionalização) initiative funds doctoral students at Brazilian federal universities to undertake sandwich doctorates — spending part of their PhD abroad — as well as attracting international postdoctoral researchers to Brazilian institutions. Within Brazil, CAPES PhD scholarships provide a monthly stipend of BRL 2,200 for doctoral students at top research universities including USP, UNICAMP, UFRJ, and UNESP. In the natural sciences, Brazil''s research strengths span tropical ecology, biodiversity, climate science, agronomy, and physics. São Paulo state''s research universities are among Latin America''s most productive, regularly publishing in top international journals and maintaining active collaborations with European and North American institutions.', 'Open to Brazilian nationals and, for postdoctoral positions, to international researchers affiliated with a Brazilian institution. PhD scholarships are granted to students enrolled in accredited doctoral programmes at Brazilian universities. International candidates seeking sandwich-doctorate or postdoctoral placements should contact Brazilian universities directly and apply through their institutional programmes.'),

-- Spain
('Spanish Government Scholarship (MAEC-AECID)', 'Spain', 'Social Sciences', 'masters', '2026-03-31', 'https://www.aecid.es/en/becas-y-convocatorias', 'The MAEC-AECID Scholarship Programme is funded by Spain''s Ministry of Foreign Affairs and administered by the Spanish Agency for International Development Cooperation (AECID). The programme awards scholarships to postgraduate students and researchers from Latin America, the Caribbean, Africa, Asia, and other regions to pursue master''s degrees, doctoral programmes, or research stays at Spanish universities and research centres. Master''s scholarships provide a monthly allowance, registration fees, health insurance, and travel contributions. Spain''s universities — the University of Barcelona, Universidad Autónoma de Madrid, Complutense Madrid, and the University of Salamanca — have strong faculties in political science, international relations, economics, and Latin American studies. The programme is particularly attractive for candidates from Ibero-American countries, for whom Spanish-language study at one of Europe''s most culturally rich nations offers unrivalled professional and cultural value.', 'Open to citizens of eligible countries in Latin America, the Caribbean, Africa, Asia, Oceania, and certain European countries. Applicants must hold a university degree equivalent to a Spanish licenciatura or grado. Candidates must not have received an AECID scholarship in the previous five years. The programme prioritises applicants with a strong connection to their home country and a clear commitment to returning after their studies.'),

-- Italy
('Italian Government Scholarship (MAECI)', 'Italy', 'Arts & Humanities', 'undergraduate', '2026-03-31', 'https://www.esteri.it/en/opportunities-and-resources/scholarships/', 'The Italian Government Scholarship for Foreign Citizens is offered by Italy''s Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation (MAECI) to foreign students, graduates, and researchers who wish to pursue undergraduate, postgraduate, or research programmes at Italian universities, academies of fine arts, music conservatories, or other higher education institutions. Scholarships cover tuition fees and a monthly allowance for the duration of the award period. Italy''s universities — La Sapienza in Rome, the University of Bologna (founded in 1088 and the world''s oldest university), the University of Milan, and the University of Florence — are world-famous centres of art history, classical studies, archaeology, architecture, design, and musicology. Studying in Italy provides scholars with incomparable proximity to the artistic, architectural, and cultural heritage that forms the foundation of Western civilisation, as well as access to Italy''s world-leading fashion, design, and food industries.', 'Open to foreign citizens who are not resident in Italy at the time of application. Age limits apply (typically under 28–30 for undergraduate scholarships, under 35–40 for research stays depending on the programme). Applicants must meet the academic requirements of the target institution. Knowledge of Italian is generally required, with language courses available in some programmes through the Società Dante Alighieri.'),

-- Turkey
('Türkiye Scholarships', 'Turkey', 'Engineering', 'undergraduate', '2026-02-20', 'https://www.turkiyeburslari.gov.tr/en', 'Türkiye Scholarships (formerly known as Turkish Government Scholarships) is one of the world''s most competitive and comprehensive government scholarship programmes, managed by the Presidency for Turks Abroad and Related Communities (YTB). The programme offers fully-funded undergraduate, master''s, and doctoral scholarships to students from more than 160 countries. Undergraduate engineering scholarships cover full tuition fees, monthly stipend, accommodation in state dormitories, Turkish language course, one-time travel allowance, and health insurance. Turkey''s technical universities — Istanbul Technical University (ITU), Middle East Technical University (METU), and Bogazici University — rank among the strongest in the region for civil, mechanical, electrical, and aerospace engineering. Türkiye Scholarships received over 150,000 applications in 2024, with only a small percentage awarded, making it highly competitive. Scholars benefit from a vibrant student community, rich historical environment, and Turkey''s growing role as a regional economic and technological hub.', 'Open to citizens of all eligible countries (excluding Turkish citizens). Undergraduate applicants must be under 21 years of age. Master''s applicants must be under 30 and hold a bachelor''s degree. PhD applicants must be under 35 and hold a master''s degree. Applicants must demonstrate strong academic performance (minimum 70% for undergraduate, 75% for postgraduate). Applications are submitted exclusively through the online Türkiye Scholarships portal.')

